# Steps to reproduce the problem
1. use attached asset.jpg
2. create ImageDecoder
3. for better reproducibility, have dev tools open so `debugger` pauses between `new ImageDecoder` and `await decoder.tracks.ready;` ... click resume script in dev tools 
4. render decoded VideoFrame into canvas via context2d
5. observe bottom line rendering glitch - the pixels are not pure black, but mix of gray/white

# Problem Description
When drawing VideoFrame obtained from ImageDecoder, it may happen that the very bottom line of pixels is not accurate, and instead of black (in this case) it renders random white/gray glitch (see attached screenshot).

Here is code to reproduce, run it in secured context and have dev tools open when running

```
<body style="background:#000;">
<img src="asset.jpg"/>
<script>
(async () => {
const data = await (await fetch("asset.jpg")).arrayBuffer();
const decoder = new ImageDecoder({type:"image/jpeg", data});

debugger;

await decoder.tracks.ready;
const {image:frame} = await decoder.decode();
decoder.close();
const canvas = document.createElement("canvas");
canvas.width = frame.displayWidth;
canvas.height = frame.displayHeight;
const ctx = canvas.getContext("2d");
ctx.drawImage(frame, 0, 0);
document.body.append(canvas);

})()
</script>
```

Reproducibility is not 100%, but the glitch appears randomly with refreshes (or in new window) on my Mac mini M2.

# Summary
ImageDecoder VideoFrame to Canvas has rendering glitch on bottom row of pixels

